               <p>WILLIAM BOWDEN. I am a <rs id="t18260914-427-viclabel2397" type="occupation">shoemaker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-427-victim2211 t18260914-427-viclabel2397"></join>, and lodge in <placeName id="t18260914-427-crimeloc2398">Rose-alley, Eagle-street, Holborn</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-427-crimeloc2398" type="placeName" value="Rose-alley, Eagle-street, Holborn"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-427-crimeloc2398" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-427-off2395 t18260914-427-crimeloc2398"></join>, at Thomas Davis' house. On the 5th of July I was awoke early in the morning by a man crossing my room - I laid still, and saw it was the prisoner - I saw him go to the box and take two pairs of trousers and a coat of Lloyd's - he took my coat, waistcoat, and trousers from the foot of the bed, and went out - I followed - he dropped them on the stairs - I gave an alarm, and a lamplighter took him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by Mr. PRENDERGAST. Q. What time was this? A. A few minutes before five o'clock - the front door is usually open - I thought, at first, it was my shopmate, and said "Halloo, you are come early;" I never lost sight of him - my things are worth 20s.</p>
               <p>JOHN LLOYD. I sleep in Bowden's room. I was not there that night - I left my things in the box - they are worth 30s.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-427-person2214">
                  FRANCIS 
                  CLARRIDGE
               <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2214" type="surname" value="CLARRIDGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2214" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2214" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman of Eagle-street. I heard the alarm, and took the prisoner from the hands of the lamplighter - he said that the man was gone down another street - Bowden was following him - I saw nobody else.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-427-person2215">
                  JOHN 
                  LLOYD
               <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2215" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2215" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-427-person2215" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I found the property at the foot of the stairs.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been at the fair, and returning home intoxicated, I heard a cry of Stop thief! I ran up and saw a man on the other side of the way - I asked him what was the matter; he said "You did it;" and took me; the watchman can prove he said he had lost sight of the person twice.</p>
               <p>FRANCIS CLARRIDGE. He did not say so.</p>
               <p>JOHN LLOYD. He did not say so.</p>
               <p>
